        caption: 'The elementary polarization step on two uses of a channel W. Two input bits are combined by a single XOR into x1 = u1 XOR u2 and x2 = u2, then sent through independent copies of W (the two-use channel W2). Reading the bits back in order splits W2 into two synthetic bit-channels: W- (decode u1 with u2 still unknown) is worse than W, and W+ (decode u2 given the already-known u1) is better. Their capacities average to I(W) exactly — capacity is conserved and merely redistributed — while the channels drift apart. On the binary erasure channel this is exact: erasure probabilities follow Z- = 2z - z^2 and Z+ = z^2, with capacity 1 - Z. Recursing the same transform n = log2 N times polarizes N channels toward capacity 0 or 1, the good fraction tending to I(W).'
